<section id="rental">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="section-label">Finding your apartment</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Rental rules in HCMC</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">Renting property as an expat in Ho Chi Minh City is generally straightforward — but there are a few key rules and expectations to know.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rental-grid">
      <div class="rental-rules reveal">
        <div class="rule-item">
          <h4>Rental contract</h4>
          <p>All agreements should be in writing. Most landlords provide a bilingual contract in both Vietnamese and English. Ensure you understand all terms and conditions before signing — if offered Vietnamese-only, request an English version or speak with our Vietnamese team.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-item">
          <h4>Deposit</h4>
          <p>Landlords typically require a deposit equivalent to two months' rent. This is usually refunded when you leave, provided there's no damage beyond normal wear and tear. Keep the deposit available in VND as international bank transfers can be problematic.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-item">
          <h4>Rent payment</h4>
          <p>Rent is generally paid monthly, though some landlords may request quarterly payments (very rare). Always clarify the payment terms before signing the lease.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-item">
          <h4>Lease duration</h4>
          <p>Lease terms are often flexible in HCMC. One year leases are most common, but shorter or longer terms can often be negotiated with the landlord.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-item">
          <h4>Registration with local police</h4>
          <p>Once you find a place, you must register your residency with the local police. Your landlord will usually assist you with this process. Our Vietnamese team can also support you.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="reveal">
        <div class="rental-tips">
          <h3>💡 Practical tips</h3>
          <ul class="tip-list">
            <li>Always work with a reputable real estate agent familiar with the local market — our current team can provide recommendations.</li>
            <li>Utilities (electricity, water, internet, cable TV) are often paid separately from rent — always check what's included before signing.</li>
            <li>Serviced apartments are available, usually including cleaning once or twice a week, with linen changes as part of the service.</li>
            <li>Both tenant and landlord have the right to terminate the lease with one to three months' notice — clarify this in your contract.</li>
            <li>Be sure to clarify your deposit return policy in cases of early termination before you sign anything.</li>
            <li>Utility bills in Vietnam are much lower than in most home countries — a pleasant surprise!</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

