<section id="transport">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="section-label">Moving around the city</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Getting around HCMC</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">Most foreigners get around by xe ôm (motorbike taxi) or regular taxi. Here's what you need to know.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="transport-grid">
      <div class="transport-card reveal">
        <h3>🛵 Motorbike</h3>
        <p>If you're considering driving yourself, you'll need a licence to ensure your insurance is valid and to present to police if pulled over. We recommend bringing your UK driving licence and getting it converted to a Vietnamese one — far easier than doing a Vietnamese driving test.</p>
        <p style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">If you wish to drive, you have the option of buying or renting a motorbike. They are inexpensive and widely available. Always stay safe and buy an EU standard helmet.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Saigon Motorcycles — good starting point</li>
          <li>DC Motorbikes — well-reviewed</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="transport-card reveal">
        <h3>🚕 Taxis & ride-hailing</h3>
        <p>Taxis are very inexpensive and easy to use. Several apps allow you to call taxis in advance, helping you get in and around traffic quickly. Once you've been here a short time, you'll soon feel comfortable on the back of a bike.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong style="color: var(--gold-light)">Grab</strong> — most popular and reliable</li>
          <li><strong style="color: var(--gold-light)">GoJek</strong> — great for bikes and cars</li>
          <li><strong style="color: var(--gold-light)">Be</strong> — popular local alternative</li>
          <li>Vinasun, Mai Linh & Vinasun — for traditional taxis</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="fare-box">
          <strong>Typical fares:</strong> Around 30,000 VND (£1) for a short journey around Thảo Điền. From Thảo Điền to the city centre: approx. 120,000–150,000 VND (£4–5).
